Hardware-in-the-loop (HIL) testing for Arduino involves emulating real-world interactions with hardware components to verify the correctness of your embedded system. To perform HIL testing, you can utilize the `HardwareSerial` library, which allows you to simulate serial communication between your Arduino board and external devices. You can also use the `Arduino Simulator` in Arduino IDE to simulate various Arduino boards and peripherals. For unit testing on the host, you can use a library like `ArduinoTest` that provides a testing framework for Arduino sketches. When writing unit tests, consider using a mocking library like `MockHardware` to isolate dependencies and make your tests more reliable. Here's an example of how you can use `ArduinoTest` to write a unit test for a simple Arduino sketch:

```cpp
#include <ArduinoTest.h>

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(9600);
}

void loop() {
  // Your loop code here
}

TEST_CASE('Serial communication test') {
  MockHardware mock(arduino);
  Serial.print('Hello, world!');
  REQUIRE(mock.serial_available() > 0);
}
```

By using these techniques, you can ensure that your Arduino-based embedded system behaves correctly in various scenarios and edge cases.
